Then it says, some of them endeavoured to produce Bibles in the languages of the common people.

00:02:29.169 --> 00:02:39.169
So let's just think for a few moments about some of those, perhaps less than 100 years before the time that Brother Russell started the watch down.

00:02:39.169 --> 00:02:49.169
How many of these were motivated to go to distant parts of the earth to translate the Bible and help others there.

00:02:49.169 --> 00:02:58.169
For example, in the year 1793, a man by the name of William Carey was a British shoemaker.

00:02:58.169 --> 00:03:04.169
And this shoemaker was very impressed with the words recorded in Matthew 28, 19, and 20.

00:03:04.169 --> 00:03:09.169
He felt strongly that all Christians should follow that command.

00:03:09.169 --> 00:03:12.169
So his goal was to go to India.

00:03:12.169 --> 00:03:20.169
And he arrived in India, faced all sorts of problems, eventually his wife died, his son died as well.

00:03:20.169 --> 00:03:23.169
He had to take a job planting indigo.

00:03:23.169 --> 00:03:34.169
But this man, within 21 years with the help of some others, was able to translate the Bible or parts of it in 36 languages.

00:03:34.169 --> 00:03:43.169
Then in 1797, another man Henry Not from England was a bricklayer.

00:03:43.169 --> 00:03:47.169
And he and quite a number of others arrived in Tahiti.

00:03:47.169 --> 00:03:56.169
Now four of those in that ship were noted to be pastors, but they had no formal training whatsoever.

00:03:56.169 --> 00:04:00.169
And Henry Not hadn't had a very good education.

00:04:00.169 --> 00:04:04.169
He was a bricklayer. He just had the basic education.

00:04:04.169 --> 00:04:12.169
But this very faithful man decided to learn Hebrew and Greek and translate the Bible into Tahiti.

00:04:12.169 --> 00:04:14.169
And he learned Tahiti very quickly.

00:04:14.169 --> 00:04:23.170
And in 1835, after 30 years of translating, it says he put down his quill and the Tahiti Bible,

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:29.170
which incidentally uses Jehovah's name in both the Hebrew and the Greek sections of the Bible.

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:37.170
Then 1807, Robert Morrison, a man who was determined to translate the Bible into Chinese.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:44.170
He arrived in China to find out that if anyone taught a foreigner Chinese, there was a death penalty.

00:04:44.170 --> 00:04:49.170
So he remained indoors for a couple of years while he learned the Chinese language.

00:04:49.170 --> 00:05:01.170
And then when he started to translate the Bible, he found out the emperor had stated there would be a death penalty for anyone who printed Christian literature in that country.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:08.170
Well, in 1819, Morrison completed his version there of the Bible.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:18.170
1812, Judson, an American, along with his wife, left America just after two weeks of marriage.

00:05:18.170 --> 00:05:28.170
And in 1813, arrived in Burma, which is now known as Myanmar, and his determination was to translate the Bible into the local language,

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:34.170
which was very hard. There was no dictionary. There was no one that could actually teach him.

00:05:34.170 --> 00:05:45.170
And yet he set to learning the language. He had a period of time where he was in prison with three pairs of iron fetus attached to his body.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:53.170
And he was very concerned about his Bible manuscript that he'd been translating, which was hidden in the earth under his home.

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:58.170
His wife eventually brought it to prison, was hidden in a pillar.

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:06.170
Well, this man by 1835 had the Bible translated into the local language there.

00:06:06.170 --> 00:06:12.170
But not all of these were white missionaries from either America or England.

00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:22.170
When the message reached the Pacific, for example, many local persons, Polynesians, were very determined to go to other islands within the Pacific.

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:37.170
And the example of this is in 1823, a man, a Polynesian by the name of Papa Iha, was determined to get the message in Buratonga in the Cook Islands.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:46.170
So the mission ship arrived there, the two missionary couples from overseas, white missionaries were put ashore.

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:57.170
There was a misunderstanding with the drunken king, which resulted in them being beaten up, all their possessions being stolen, and then fleeing back to the ship.

00:06:57.170 --> 00:07:04.170
But Papa Iha was determined to take the gospel message to those islanders.

00:07:04.170 --> 00:07:08.170
So it's reported that he said that he would swim ashore.

00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:20.170
And he called out, which translated means, Jehovah is my shepherd, I am in his hand.

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:30.170
And holding a book with some translations of the Bible interhesion, he jumped overboard, swam ashore, and started preaching to the local people.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:34.170
Well, you can't help but admire that enthusiasm.

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:40.170
The conditions that these missionaries met were very, very difficult, very primitive conditions.

00:07:40.170 --> 00:07:54.170
In one country, the missionaries lived in villages where people still practice cannibalism, and in many cases where the chief died, all his wives were executed at that point and buried with him.

00:07:54.170 --> 00:08:06.170
So in the midst of these conditions, these men translated the Bible and in many cases used Jehovah's name, not only in the Bible but in their personal writings.

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:12.170
What kept them going? What helped them to go to these distant parts of the earth?

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:18.170
Well, a book on the history of the missionary work in the Pacific makes this interesting comment.

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:28.170
It says, strong faith in Jehovah often overcame fear and despair. What an interesting thought.

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:33.169
Well, the obvious question is, were these ones anointed?

00:08:33.169 --> 00:08:37.169
